===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} – depiction uncertain. Some propose it depicts a plant's roots underground, possibly as the original form of {{och-l|荄}}. Others propose it is an animal, similar in origin to [[豕]].

===Etymology===
{{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} groups {{och-l|亥}} in a word-family meaning "root, germ, generative core" along with {{och-l|荄|tr=*kɯ:|grassroot}} → {{och-l|根|root}}, {{och-l|核|id=2|germ, kernel}}, {{och-l|骸|(human) bones}}, and {{och-l|孩|child}}. He suggests the derivation 荄根 "germ, sprout, root (n.)" → 孩 "to sprout" → 亥 "sprouting stage", i.e. "the moon’s first appearance", recalling {{zh-l|月芽}} lit. "moon sprout" → "crescent moon".

See {{zh-l|核}} for further etymology.

Later {{zh-l|亥}} and {{zh-l|豕|pig}} graphically converged.

As for {{och-l|亥}}'s phonological association with the pig. Compare the following:
* {{cog|km|កុរ||year of the pig}}, from {{cog|okz-ang|kur}}.
* {{cog|mkh-vie-pro|*guːrʔ|t=pig; pork}} or {{m|mkh-vie-pro|*kuːrʔ|t=pig; pork}}:
** {{cog|vi|cúi||''(archaic)'' pig}}
** {{cog|mtq|củi|tr=kuːj³|t=pig}}
** {{cog|scb|cûl|tr=kûːl|t=pig}}
* {{cog|th|กุน||year of the pig}}, a loan from Old Khmer.
{{zh-ref|Ferlus (2013)}} notes {{och-l|亥}} is a possible match to the Austroasiatic root, but there should be a final sonorant in Old Chinese.

